<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1683,1812]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,1683,1708]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Remarks</emphasis>
. There have been no recent revisions of the 
<taxonomicName box="[793,924,1683,1708]" class="Malacostraca" family="Cirolanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cirolanidae</taxonomicName>
for the tropical Western Atlantic. The only comprehensive accounts are the now dated monograph 
<emphasis box="[773,1114,1717,1742]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">The Isopods of North America</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Richardson" box="[1128,1423,1717,1742]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" refString="Richardson, H. (1905) A monograph on the isopods of North America (No. 54). US Government Printing Office, Washington, pp. 81 - 137." type="book chapter" year="1905">Richardson 1905: 81â€“137</bibRefCitation>
), and the more recent Caribbean field guide by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kensley" box="[694,999,1752,1777]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" refString="Kensley, B. &amp; Schotte, M. (1989) Guide to the marine isopod crustaceans of the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, D. C. &amp; London, 129 pp." type="book" year="1989">Kensley &amp; Schotte (1989)</bibRefCitation>
is also relevant. For identification of marine cirolanids recourse is still to the primary literature and databases such as WoRMS.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
